QuestÃ£o 3

FacÌ§a um graÌfico de dispersaÌo entre as variaÌveis hwy e cyl. Mude a cor do tema. Interprete os resultados.

  • O grÃ¡fico aparenta haver uma tendÃªncia negativa entre o o nÃºmero de cilindros e a autonomia do automÃ³vel na rodovia. Quanto mais cilindros o carro tem, menor Ã© a distÃ¢ncia em milhas por galÃ£o que o mesmo pode percorrer na rodovia.
mydata %>% 
      ggplot(aes(y = hwy, x = cyl)) + 
      geom_point(aes(colour = class) ) +
      labs(title = "Correlation between number of cylinders and highway miles per gallon", 
             x = "Number of cylinders", y = "Highway miles per gallon") + 
      theme_bw() +
      theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5, size = 12))

QuestÃ£o 5

Escoha duas variaÌveis do banco de dados e construa histograma e box-plot para elas. Personalize os graÌficos usando cores diferentes do default. NaÌo se esquecÌ§a de dar nom espara os eixos, bem como um tÃ­tulo para os graÌficos. Organize os graÌficos em subplots usando gride.arrange(). Note que teremos 2 histogramas e 2 boxplots, totalizando graÌficos que vc deve plotar em duas colunas.

hg1 = mydata %>%
    ggplot() + 
    geom_histogram(aes(x = hwy), bins = 20, colour = "black", fill = "coral2") +
    labs(title = "Highway miles per gallon - Histogram", x = "miles per gallon", y = "Count") +
    theme_bw() +   
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5,size = 11), axis.title = element_text(size = 9))

bp1 = mydata %>%
    ggplot() + 
    geom_boxplot(aes(y = hwy), colour = "black", fill = "coral2") +
    labs(title = "Highway miles per gallon - Boxplot", y = "miles per gallon") +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5,size = 11), axis.title = element_text(size = 9))

hg2 = mydata %>%
    ggplot() + 
    geom_histogram(aes(x = cty), bins = 20, colour = "black", fill = "slateblue2") +
    labs(title =  "City miles per gallon - Histogram", x = "miles per gallon", y = "Count") +
    theme_bw() +   
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5,size = 11), axis.title = element_text(size = 9))

bp2 = mydata %>%
    ggplot() + 
    geom_boxplot(aes(y = cty), colour = "black", fill = "slateblue2") +
    labs(title = "City miles per gallon - Boxplot", y = "miles per gallon") +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5,size = 11), axis.title = element_text(size = 9))


grid.arrange(hg1, bp1, hg2, bp2, ncol = 2, top = "Distribution of city miller per gallon and highway miles per gallon")

QuestÃ£o 6

Usando o arquivo de dados mpg ainda, vamos agora treinar o uso do recurso facet.

6.1

FacÌ§a graÌficos de dispersaÌo entre displ e hwy separados para cada classe de veÄ±Ìculos. Use color = class para diferenciar por cor e facet_wrap( â¼ class, nrow=2) para obter os subplots

mydata %>% 
      ggplot(aes(y = displ, x = hwy)) + 
      geom_point(aes(colour = class) ) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
      labs(title = "Correlation between fuel consumption on the highway and engine displacement", 
           y = "Engine displacement (l)", x = "Highway miles per gallon") + 
      theme_bw() +
      theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 11), legend.position="none") + 
      facet_wrap(~ class ,ncol =  2)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

6.2

Agora vamos criar subplots com base em duas variaÌveis: nuÌmero de cilindros (cyl) e tipo de direcÌ§aÌo (drv). Diferencie por cor usando color=drv e utilize facet_grid(drv â¼cyl). Algumas facetas ficaraÌo vazias por naÌo possuÄ±Ìrem combinacÌ§oÌes de drv e cyl.

mydata %>% 
      ggplot() + 
      geom_point(mapping = aes(x = cyl, y = drv, colour = drv)) +
      labs(title = "Correlation between type of drive train and number of cylinders", 
           y = "Type of drive train", x = "Number of cylinders") + 
      theme_bw() +
      theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 11), legend.position="none") + 
      facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

6.3

Explique o que ocorre se voceÌ usar color=cyl para classifcar por cilindros (cyl) e facet_grid(. â¼ cyl).

  • O sÃ­mbolo . ignora determinada dimensÃ£o ao gerar os subplots. Por exemplo, ao usar facet_grid(. â¼ cyl), gerou-se subplots a partir dos valores de cyl no eixo-x e coloriu os pontos de acordo com os nÃ­veis dessa variÃ¡vel.
mydata %>% 
      ggplot() + 
      geom_point(mapping = aes(x = cyl, y = drv, colour = cyl)) +
      labs(title = "Correlation between type of drive train and number of cylinders", 
           y = "Type of drive train", x = "Number of cylinders") + 
      theme_bw() +
      theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 11)) + 
      facet_grid(.~ cyl)

7.1

Construa um diagrama de dispersaÌo entre as variaÌveis CPI (eixo x) e HDI (eixo y). Coloque a cor vermelha nos pontos.

homework3 %>% 
      ggplot(aes(x = CPI, y = HDI)) + 
      geom_point(color = "red", size = 3) +
      scale_shape_identity() +
      labs(title = "Correlation between human development and corruption perception",  
           y = "Human Development Index, 2011 (1 = best)", x = "Corruption Perceptions Index, 2011 (10 = least corrupt)") + 
      theme_bw() +
      theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 9, face = "italic")) +
      scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0,10, 1), limits = c(1, 10)) +
      scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1), limits = c(0.2, 1))

7.5

O arquivo Economist1.pdf disponÄ±Ìvel junto com a lista de exercÄ±Ìcios apresenta um graÌfico usando os dados contidos no arquivo que estamos usando. Escreva um coÌdigo no R usando ggplot que replica taÌo proÌximo quanto possÄ±Ìvel o graÌfico em questaÌo.

  • Criar um subset com os paÃ­ses listados no grÃ¡fico modelo
# Define os paÃ­ses que se quer filtrar
target  = c("Congo", "Afghanistan" , "Sudan", "Myanmar", "Iraq", "Venezuela", "India", "South Africa", "China", "Argentina", "Russia", "Greece", "Brazil", "Italy", "Rwanda", "Cape Verde", "Bhutan", "Botswana", "Spain", "France", "US", "Germany", "Britain", "Barbados", "Japan", "Norway", "New Zealand", "Singapore")

# Cria o subset temporÃ¡rio a partir da filtragem dos paÃ­ses listados
temp = homework3 %>%
  select(CPI, HDI, Country) %>%
  filter(Country %in% target)

head(temp)
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
##     CPI   HDI Country    
##   <dbl> <dbl> <chr>      
## 1   1.5 0.398 Afghanistan
## 2   3   0.797 Argentina  
## 3   7.8 0.793 Barbados   
## 4   5.7 0.522 Bhutan     
## 5   6.1 0.633 Botswana   
## 6   3.8 0.718 Brazil
  • Plotagem do grÃ¡fico
homework3 %>% 
      ggplot(aes(x = CPI, y = HDI)) + 
      geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Region), shape = 21, size = 2, stroke = 1.1) +
      scale_shape_identity() +
      geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y~log(x), se = FALSE, color = "red") + 
      labs(title = "Corruption and human development",  
           y = "Human Development Index, 2011 (1 = best)", x = "Corruption Perceptions Index, 2011 (10 = least corrupt)") + 
      theme_bw() +
      theme(legend.position = "top", axis.title = element_text(size = 9, face = "italic")) +
      scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0,10, 1), limits = c(1, 10)) +
      scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1), limits = c(0.2, 1)) +
      geom_text_repel(data = temp, aes(label = Country),
                  box.padding   = 0.35,
                  nudge_y  = 0.1,
                  nudge_x  = 0.2,
                  segment.size  = 0.2,
                  point.padding = 0.5,
                  segment.color = 'grey50')
